        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Aldine Hotel<lb/>
                October 6<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1883<lb/></p>
                
            <p>My Dear Mr Morais&#45;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>I went out to the<lb/> Eastern Penitentiary and in&#45;<lb/>terviewed Jacobs&#8212;He called<lb/> me Belmont&#45;&#45; Beyond all doubt<lb/> he is insane&#8212;The Warden<lb/> told me that he was well treated&#44;<lb/> and I found him with his<lb/> pipe in his mouth&#44; taking his<lb/> ease&#8212;The food he receives is<lb/> plain&#44; but good&#44; and I am<lb/> impressed with the belief<lb/> that his condition is really<lb/> better there&#44; than with a pro&#45;<lb/>miscuous crowd of insane&#45;&#45;<lb/> Excepting the taint which<lb/> a prison life conveys. I think<lb/> he is better off where he now is.<lb/> His daughter visited him&#44; and<lb/> if you desire I will <hi rend="underline">go</hi> and<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>see that his family are not<lb/> destitute&#8212;By sending me<lb/> their address to N<hi rend="sup">o</hi> 223 <lb/>South 5th St my old place<lb/> of business where I can be <lb/> seen <hi rend="underline">daily</hi> from 10&#95;A.M. To<lb/> 11&#95;O.C.<lb/></p>
            <p>With kind regards<lb/> I remain<lb/>			Truly&#95;&#95;<lb/>
                Lucien Moss</p>
        </body>
    </text>
